Bio LPG arrives in the Czech Republic, promises ecological operation
Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) is a well-known alternative fuel in the Czech Republic.
It is especially popular because of its significantly lower price compared to gasoline or diesel, given a significantly lower excise tax, but its benefit is also in lower CO2 emissions per kilometre travelled.
Like gasoline and diesel, it has its own environmentally friendly variant - "bio LPG".
However, this is quite a novelty - it first appeared on the European market a few years ago and arrived in the Czech Republic a few days ago, according to a press release from the Czech LPG Association.
"In these days, we have received the first fifteen tons of bio LPG, which will be distributed to our petrol stations in combination with conventional fossil LPG," said Ji<0xC5><0x99>í Karlík of Primagas.
However, bio-LPG cannot be considered as bioethanol or biodiesel.
According to the association, it is chemically identical to the classic petroleum LPG, which many motorists are refueling their cars now.
Therefore, it is also possible to mix both versions arbitrarily.
"The only difference compared to conventional LPG is the production method," says Ivan Indrá<0xC4><0x8D>ek, chairman of the association, about bio LPG.
This is one of the great advantages of bio-LPG compared to other alternative fuels.
It can be easily transported and stored, and the distribution infrastructure is also quite good, e.g. compared to hydrogen or electricity.
Currently, this gas is obtained as a by-product in the production of bioethanol from food residues and sugar cane.
In the future, it should also be produced specifically, e.g. from cellulose biomass, i.e. from wood waste.
In contrast, classical petroleum LPG is produced partly as a by-product in the refining of oil, partly by separation in the extraction of natural gas.
As a result, depending on the production technology and source, the operation of the bio-LPG car is 40-70% more environmentally friendly in terms of carbon footprint than that of petroleum LPG and up to 90% compared to diesel.
However, it is not about CO2 emissions from the exhaust of the car, but about the ecology of fuel production, i.e. the so-called "well-to-tank" part (in Czech "from source to tank").
One of the largest producers of organic LPG currently includes petrochemical companies Eni, Total and Neste.
According to a recent update of the National Clean Mobility Action Plan (NAP <0xC4><0x8C>M), Unipetrol is also exploring the possibility of production at its Litvínov refinery.
According to the estimates of the Association in the Czech Republic, about 170,000 LPG-powered vehicles drive; the Ministry of Environment reports a slightly higher number, about 200,000, in the NAP <0xC4><0x8C>M.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Transport, almost 6 thousand conversions of LPG-powered cars were carried out last year alone.
LPG refuelling is possible in the Czech Republic at about 950 stations of different operators.
