According to experts, the Chiquihuite cave, located at high altitude, has been inhabited for 20,000 years.
A widely accepted theory so far has suggested that the first representatives of Homo sapiens crossed the mainland bridge from the area of present-day Russia to Alaska about 13,500 years ago.
Archaeological evidence, including unique spearheads used to kill mammoths and other prehistoric animals, showed that this Clovis culture subsequently spread across much of North America.
This model, however, got cracked in recent decades when several ancient settlements were discovered that were two to three thousand years older.
The second study, published in the journal Nature, reports on 42 different locations across North America that prove human presence on the continent as early as 26,000 to 19,000 years ago.
Scientists believe that a small number of people may have arrived on the North American mainland earlier than previously thought.
Some of them were able to get to America by boat.
"It is clear that humans were in America long before the development of the so-called Clovis culture," said anthropologist Ruth Gruhn of the University of Alberta in Canada.
