The air in homes is up to five times worse than outdoor air.
Health harms air fresheners and deodorants
Health is threatened not only by poor air quality in outdoor areas, but also at home.
This was pointed out by Israeli health expert Carol Abraham, quoted by The Jerusalem Post.
According to Abraham, who helped create Israel’s Ministry of the Environment, the focus should be on household pollutants now that many people spend more time working from home.
According to research by the U.S. Environmental Agency (EPA), indoor air quality is up to five times worse than outdoor air quality.
The World Health Organization (WHO) estimates that 3.8 million people die prematurely each year due to poor air quality in their homes.
“Because of the coronavirus epidemic, which has forced and still forces many to work from home, people have to spend more hours in their homes than before, so it’s time to focus on home air quality,” she said.
In Israel, almost no one is concerned with the quality of the “domestic air”.
Dangerous can be things that a person normally comes into contact with - paints, air fresheners, disinfectants, deodorants or pesticides.
"The clothes we regularly wear to the dry cleaners also emit poisonous gas," Abraham said.
The most at risk are children, elderly household members and people with respiratory problems.
Even otherwise healthy individuals may begin to suffer problems such as headaches, fainting, irritability of the nasal passages, nosebleeds, vomiting or skin allergies.
With prolonged exposure to unhealthy substances, internal organs and the central nervous system can be damaged.
Not all pollutants come from objects inside the home, but the material from which the homes are built can be a source.
